=Robert Evans Greer\n|birth_date= {{Birth date|df=yes|1915|8|7}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|df=yes|1976|2|11|1915|8|7}}\n|image=File:Robert Evans Greer.jpg\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place= [[Orange, California]]\n|death_place=[[Escondido, California]]\n|placeofburial=Westminster Memorial Park, [[Westminster, California]] \n|placeofburial_label= Place of burial\n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= {{ulist|[[File:US Department of the Army seal.png|23px]] [[United States Army]] (1939\u20131947)|\n[[File:US Department of the Air Force seal.png|23px]] [[United States Air Force]] (1947\u20131965)}}\n|serviceyears=1939\u20131965\n|servicenumber=AO-21910\n|rank= [[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|30px]] [[Major General (United States)|Major General]]\n|unit=\n|commands=\n|battles=World War II:{{ulist|[[China-Burma-India Theater]]|[[Air raids on Japan]]|[[Occupation of Japan]]}}\n|awards=[[Legion of Merit]]<br/>[[Army Commendation Medal]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n'''Robert Evans Greer''' (7 August 1915 \u2013 11 February 1976) was a [[United States Air Force]] (USAF) officer who attained the rank of [[major general (United States)|major general]].  A graduate of the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point, New York]], where he was ranked 175th in the class of 1939, he served in China and the Mariana Islands during World War II. After the war he served in the USAF Office of the Assistant for Atomic Energy and as vice commander of the [[Space Systems Division]] of the [[Air Force Systems Command]].\n\n== Early life ==\nRobert Evans Greer was born in [[Orange, California]], on 7 August 1915, the son of Jack and Agnes May Greer. His father was a  [[captain (U.S. Army)|captain]] in the [[United States Army Air Corps]], and the family moved frequently. He was attended [[Coronado High School (California)|Coronado High School]] on [[California]], Manila Central High School in the Philippines, and [[Huntington Beach High School]] in California, from whence he graduated in 1932. He then attended [[Santa Ana Junior College]] from 1933 to 1934, and [[Millard's Preparatory School]] in [[Washington, DC]].{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}}\n\nIn 1935, Greer secured an appointment to the [[United States Military Academy]] at [[West Point, New York]], from [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Carter Glass]] of [[Virginia]],{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}} and entered on 1 July 1935. {{sfn|Cullum|1940|p=1269}} He played [[College football]] in all four of his years at West Point. He also participated in [[Sport of athletics|athletics]], and, in his last two years, the Hundredth Night Shows, demonstrating his ability as a dancer.{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}} He graduated on 12 June 1939, ranked 175th in the Class of 1939, and was commissioned as a [[US Second Lieutenant|second lieutenant]] in the  [[United States Army Coast Artillery Corps|Coast Artillery Corps]].{{sfn|Cullum|1940|p=1269}}\n\n== World War II==\nGreer first attended the Primary Flying School at [[Glendale, California]] from 12 September to 22 December 1939,{{sfn|Cullum|1940|p=1269}} then the Basic Flying School at [[Randolph Field, Texas]], from 2 January to 12 March 40, and finally the Advanced Flying School at [[Kelly Field, Texas]], from  which he graduated on 22 June 1940. He remained there as an instructor until 1 January 1941, with the rank of  [[US First Lieutenant|first lieutenant]] in the [[Army of the United States]] from 9 September 1940. He was assigned to [[Gunter Field]] in [[Alabama]], and then [[Hendricks Army Airfield]] in [[Florida]], as the Post Engineering Officer. He was promoted to [[Captain (U.S. Army)|captain]] on 1 February and [[Major (United States)|major]] on 26 September 1942.{{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}} He married Geraldine Roberts in December 1939; by August 1945 they had four children: Virginia, Robert, James and Gery.{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}} \n\nOn 9 October 1943, Greer joined the [[58th Bombardment Wing]] at [[Smoky Hill Army Air Field, Kansas]], as its assistant operations officer (A-3), with the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] from 5 February 1944. In March, he became part of the first [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress]] air crew to depart for the [[China-Burma-India Theater]]. From 2 August 1944 to 8 February 1945, he served on the staff of the [[XX Bomber Command]].{{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}<ref name=\"USAF\" /> The B-29s suffered from numerous mechanical problems owing to their being rushed into service, and their engines lasted only about 50 hours of running time before they needed to be replaced. Greer arranged for 250 engines to be flown in from [[Casablanca]] to [[Calcutta]].{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}}{{sfn|Cate|1953|p=76}} For his service with the XX Bomber Command, he was awarded the [[Legion of Merit]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Robert Greer \u2013 Recipient  |publisher=Military Times  |url=https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/390322 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The 58th Bombardment Wing moved to [[Tinian]] in the Mariana Islands in March 1945, and Greer became its deputy chief of staff for supply and maintenance (A-4). After the war ended he served on [[Iwo Jima]] and then [[Hokkaido]].{{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}<ref name=\"USAF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/106907/major-general-robert-evans-greer/ |title=Major General Robert Evans Greer |publisher=US Air Force |access-date=10 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Postwar==\nGreer returned to the United States in September 1945, in a [[1945 Japan\u2013Washington flight|record-setting long-distance flight]] from Hokkaido to Chicago.{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}}  His first post-war assignment was at [[Wright Field, Ohio]], as assistant to the chief of administration for technical matters of the [[Air Materiel Command]] from 1 February to 29 August 1946. He was then selected as an instructor in [[electrical engineering]] at West Point. As a preliminary, he attended [[Columbia University]] from 26 September 1946 to 26 May 1947. He then taught at West Point until 22 July 1949. He transferred to the newly-formed [[United States Air Force]] (USAF) on 1 July 1948, and on 23 July 1949 he was assigned to USAF Headquarters at [[The Pentagon]] in Washington, DC, where he worked in the Office of the Assistant for Atomic Energy. He was promoted to  [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] on 22 June 1950.{{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}<ref name=\"USAF\" /> He attended the [[Air War College]], remaining as an instructor after graduation in 1953.<ref name=\"USAF\" />  He was posted to [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe]] (SHAPE) in [[Paris]] on July 1954, to serve on the staff of British [[Field Marshal (United Kingdom)|Field Marshal]] [[Lord Montgomery]]. Afterwards he joined the staff of the [[49th Air Division]] in the UK, and then the [[Third Air Force]] there as its director of operations and deputy chief of staff for operations.{{sfn|Laurie|Suk|2019|p=46}}\n\nIn July 1957, Greer returned to USAF Headquarters as the deputy assistant chief of staff and then, in July 1959, assistant chief of staff for guided missiles with the rank of  [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]]. He then became the [[Air Force Ballistic Missile Division]]'s vice commander for satellite systems. In the wake of a reorganization of the [[Air Research and Development Command]] and the [[Air Materiel Command]] on 1 April 1961, he became the vice commander of the [[Air Force Systems Command]]'s [[Space Systems Division]] (SSD), which was based at [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]] and later [[El Segundo, California]]. He was promoted to [[Major general (United States)|major general]] in July 1961.{{sfn|Laurie|Suk|2019|p=46}}\nAs vice commander of SSD, was also head of the [[Samos (satellite)|SAMOS]] Program Office. As such, he reported directly to the [[United States Under Secretary of the Air Force|Under Secretary of the Air Force]], [[Joseph V. Charyk]]. He was also the West Coast director in the USAF Office of Missile and Satellite Systems. In July 1961, the SAMOS Project Office became the USAF element of the [[National Reconnaissance Office]] (NRO). The USAF element became Program A on 23 July 1962, and embraced both the NRO Defense Meteorological Satellite Program and the secret reconnaissance satellite programs.{{sfn|Laurie|Suk|2019|p=46}} \n\nGreer retired on 1 July 1965,<ref name=\"USAF\" /> but elected to remain in southern California. He became president of a division of [[Rockwell International]]. He died from [[pancreatic cancer]] in [[Escondido, California]] on 11 February 1976, and was buried in Westminster Memorial Park in [[Westminster, California]].{{sfn|Assembly|1994|p=169}}\n\n==Dates of rank==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Insignia !! Rank !! Component !! Date || Reference\n|-\n|[[File:US-O1 insignia.svg|13px|center]]\n|[[US Second Lieutenant|Second lieutenant]] || [[United States Army Coast Artillery Corps|Coast Artillery Corps]] || 12 June 1939 || {{sfn|Cullum|1940|p=1269}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O2 insignia.svg|13px|center]]\n| [[US First Lieutenant|First lieutenant]] || [[Army of the United States]] || 9 September 1940 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Captain (U.S. Army)|Captain]] || Army of the United States || 1 February 1942 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O2 insignia.svg|13px|center]]\n| [[US First Lieutenant|First lieutenant]] || [[United States Army Air Corps|Air Corps]] || 12 June 1942 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Major (United States)|Major]] || Army of the United States || 26 September 1942 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]] ||  Army of the United States || 5 February 1944 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]] || United States Air Force || 1 July 1948  || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O5 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]]  || United States Air Force || 22 June 1948 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O6 insignia.svg|66px|center]]\n| [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]  || United States Air Force || 22 June 1950 || {{sfn|Cullum|1950|p=1003}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|33px|center]]\n| [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier general]] || United States Air Force || 1959 ||  {{sfn|Laurie|Suk|2019|p=46}}\n|-\n|[[File:US-O8 insignia.svg|66px|center]]\n| [[Major general (United States)|Major general]] || United States Air Force || July 1961 ||  {{sfn|Laurie|Suk|2019|p=46}}\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |journal=Assembly |issn= 1041-2581 |volume=53 |issue=1 |date=September 1994  |title=Robert Evans Greer |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7ozIU4l0zfYC&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169 |access-date=10 April 2020 |ref=CITEREFAssembly1994}}\n* {{cite book |last=Cate |first=James Lee |year=1953 |contribution=Part I. The Twentieth Air Force and Matterhorn |editor-first=Wesley Frank |editor-last=Craven |editor2-first=James Lea |editor2-last=Cate |series=[[The Army Air Forces in World War II]] |volume=Volume V |title=The Pacific: Matterhorn to Nagasaki June 1944 to August 1945 |publisher=Air Force Historical Studies Office |url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/AAF/V/index.html |access-date=11 April 2020 |pages=5\u2013178 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book  | title = Biographical Register of the Officers and Graduates of the US Military Academy at West Point New York Since Its Establishment in 1802: Supplement Volume VIII 1930\u20131940  | last = Cullum  | first = George W.  | author-link = George Washington Cullum  | publisher = R. R. Donnelly and Sons, The Lakeside Press  | location = Chicago  | year = 1940  | url=http://digital-library.usma.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p16919coll3/id/24660/rec/9  | access-date=6 October 2015  |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book  | title = Biographical Register of the Officers and Graduates of the US Military Academy at West Point New York Since Its Establishment in 1802: Supplement Volume IX 1940\u20131950  | last = Cullum  | first = George W.  | author-link = George Washington Cullum  | publisher = R. R. Donnelly and Sons, The Lakeside Press  | location = Chicago  | year = 1950  | url=http://digital-library.usma.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/p16919coll3/id/22314/rec/10  | access-date=6 October 2015  |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Laurie |first=Clayton |last2=Suk |first2=Michael J. |title=Leaders of the National Reconnaissance Office: Directors, Deputy Directors, Staff Directors, Program Directors, Chiefs Of Staff, Directorate and Office Managers |volume=Volume I: 1961\u20131992|edition=Second Revised Edition  |publisher=Center for the Study of National Reconnaissance |date=July 2019 |location=Chantilly, Virginia |isbn=978-1-937219-15-4 |url=https://www.nro.gov/Portals/65/documents/history/csnr/leaders/Leaders_of_NRO_Vol_I_July_2019_web.pdf?ver=2019-09-18-094920-410&timestamp=1568815046728 |access-date=10 April 2020 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greer, Robert Evans}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Air War College alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force generals]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces pilots of World War II]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Cuprum17", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld War II:date style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Evans_Greer"}
{"title_page": "Znamenny chant", "text_new": "{{for|the Znamenny Icon of the Theotokos|Our Lady of the Sign}}\n[[Image:Example of hooks and banners notation.PNG|thumb|300px|right|An example of Znamenny notation with so-called \"red marks\", Russia, 1884. \"Thy [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Cross]] we honour, oh Lord, and Thy holy Resurrection we praise.\"]]\n\n'''Znamenny Chant''' ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435, \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0432}}) is a singing tradition used by some in the [[Russia]]n [[Orthodox Church]]. Znamenny Chant is [[unison]], [[melisma]]tic [[liturgy|liturgical]] singing that has its own specific notation, called the ''stolp'' notation.  The symbols used in the stolp notation are called ''{{transl|ru|kryuki|links=no}}'' ({{lang-ru|\u043a\u0440\u044e\u043a\u0438|links=no}}, 'hooks') or ''{{transl|ru|znamena}}'' ({{lang-ru|\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0451\u043d\u0430|links=no}}, 'signs').  Often the names of the signs are used to refer to the stolp notation.  Znamenny melodies are part of a system, consisting of Eight Tones (intonation structures; called glasy); the melodies are characterized by fluency and well-balancedness {{harv|Kholopov|2003|loc=192}}. There exist several types of Znamenny Chant: the so-called ''Stolpovoy'', ''Malyj'' (Little) and ''Bolshoy'' (Great) Znamenny Chant.  Ruthenian Chant ([[Prostopinije]]) is sometimes considered a sub-division of the Znamenny Chant tradition, with the [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Muscovite]] Chant (Znamenny Chant proper) being the second branch of the same musical continuum.\n\n==Notation==\nZnamenny Chants are not written with notes (the so-called linear notation), but with special signs, called ''Znam\u00ebna'' (Russian for \"marks\", \"banners\") or ''Kryuki'' (\"hooks\"), as some shapes of these signs resemble hooks. Each sign may include the following components: a large black hook or a black stroke, several smaller black 'points' and 'commas' and lines near the hook or crossing the hook. Some signs may mean only one note, some 2 to 4 notes, and some a whole melody of more than 10 notes with a complicated rhythmic structure. [[Image:Kryuki.jpg|thumb|200px|A hand-drawn [[lubok]] featuring 'hook and banner notation'.]]\n\nThe stolp notation was developed in [[Kievan Rus']] as an [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] refinement of the [[Byzantine music|Byzantine]] [[neumatic]] musical notation.\n\nThe most notable feature of this notation system is that it records transitions of the melody, rather than [[Musical note|note]]s. The signs also represent a mood and a gradation of how this part of melody is to be sung (tempo, strength, devotion, meekness, etc.) Every sign has its own name and also features as a spiritual symbol. For example, there is a specific sign, called \"little dove\" (Russian: \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u0447\u0438\u043a ''(golubchik)''), which represents two rising sounds, but which is also a symbol of the [[Holy Ghost]].\n\nAfter the fall of Kievan Rus' to the [[Mongols]], the Znamenny Chant and stolp notation continued to develop to the North (particularly in [[Novgorod]]), where it flourished and was adopted throughout the [[Grand Duchy of Moscow]].\n\nGradually the system became more and more complicated. This system was also ambiguous, so that almost no one, except the most trained and educated singers, could sing an unknown melody at sight. The signs only helped to reproduce the melody, not coding it in an unambiguous way.\n\nBecause of the complexity of the system, a simplification was developed by Ivan Shaidurov around 1600,<ref>Velimirovic, Milos. \"The Present status of Research in Slavic Chant\". ''Acta Musicologica''. Vol. 44, Fasc. 2 (Jul. \u2013 Dec., 1972), pp. 251</ref> called \"red marks\" (Russian: \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u0438 (''kinovarnye znaki'')), which consisted of small letters in red and which were placed before each Znamenny sign. These indicate the highest note of the sign it stands before. This is generally regarded as the first step towards a certain simplification of the system.\n\nThe use and evolution of the system stopped in the middle of the 17th century, after the [[raskol|church reforms]] by [[Patriarch Nikon]]. From that time Western music started to penetrate into Russian culture, and the Russian-Orthodox Church introduced a \"Latin\", polyphonic way of singing, based on Polish, German and Italian harmonies. The term \"Latin\" however was considered derogatory, since it also referred to \"heretical Latin faith\".  Znamenny Chant, however, has been preserved to a certain degree in the chanting traditions that are directly descended from it.\n\n[[File:\u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0438\u043d. \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0445\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0415\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u044f, \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441 1. \u0420\u0430\u0441\u0448\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u041c. \u0412..ogg|thumb|left|Fyodor Krestianin (i.e. Christian). Sticheron first of Gospel, mode 1. Transcribing of M.Brazhnikov]]\nCurrently, stolp notation (Znamenny signs) continues to be used by Russian [[Old Believers]], mostly in combination with the above-mentioned \"red marks\", as shown in the first illustration. In the 19th century [[Edinovertsy]], particularly outside Russia, have tried to move to the modern neumatic form of notation that tries to capture exact relations between [[pitch (music)|pitch]]es; and they currently use a standard [[musical notation|linear notation]].\n\nChanting traditions that preserve and/or are descended from the Znammeny chant include the following:\n\n* Chanting traditions of the Russian [[Old Believers]]\n** Znamenny chant proper (\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f, \u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0435 \u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f)\n** Stolpovoy chant\n** [[Demesvenny chant]] or ''Demestvo'' (\u0414\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e)\n** [[Pomorsky chant]]\n** [[Kievan chant]]\n* '[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] Chants'\n** The chanting tradition of [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] (known as [[Samoilka]] chant)\n** [[Prostopinije]] (or Plain Chant) of the [[Rusyns|Carpatho-Rusyns]]\n* [[Valaam chant]]\n*  Doukhobor Psalm chant may also be derivative or at least related\ncf. F. Mark Mealing/Our People's Way/A Study in Doukhobor Hymnody & Folklife. U. Penna, 1972.\nThe [[Strochnoy chant]] (early Russian [[polyphony]]) was also based on Znamenny chant, and although it is not widely used in the church practice now, it can be occasionally performed by some choirs. Many Russian composers ([[Sergei Rachmaninov]], [[Alexander Grechaninov]], [[Maximilian Steinberg]], and [[Vladimir Martynov]]) studied Znamenny chants and used them in their compositions. There are also many adaptations of Znamenny melodies for four-part choir, popular in both Russia and abroad.\n\n==Performing practice==\nBecause Znamenny Chant requires a specific manner of performance, the chant books contain several instructions as to dynamics and tempo. For the Old Believers church chant also has an educational function: one has to sing in such a way that the sound astonishes the ear and the truth, enclosed in the chants, penetrates the heart. Znamenny performance practice excludes classical vocal training.  Singers perform with their own, natural voices, sometimes in a style reminiscent of folk music. Znamenny Chant does not have any pauses or rests, and all chants are performed fluently. Ideally, singers will sing in such a way that their voices become united in one single voice.   \nOriginally Znamenny Chant was performed only by male voices. Today, on account of the small number of people able to sing at church services and the evolution of the tradition, it is usually performed by both male and female voices.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kholopov|2003}}|reference=[[Yuri Kholopov|Kholopov, Yuri]] (2003). ''\u0413\u0430\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u0422\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441''. 2nd ed. Moscow; Saint Petersburg: Lan'. {{ISBN|5-8114-0516-2}} (English: Harmony. A Theoretical Course; the 1st ed. is Moscow, 1988)}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \u0412\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0444\u0442 \u0421.\u0413., \u0423\u0448\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0418.\u0410. \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0440\u044f\u0434\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e. \u041b\u0438\u0446\u0430, \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u044f, \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043c\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044b. \u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442 \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f, \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 1996 / Vurgaft S.G., U\u0161akov I.A. Staroobrjad\u010destvo. Lica, sobytija, predmety i simvoly. Opyt \u0117nciklopedi\u010deskogo slovarja, Moskva 1996 \n* Reynolds, Steven.  \"Carpatho-Rusyn American\", Vol. II (1979), No. 3.  Carpatho-Rusyn Research Society.\n\n==External links ==\n{{commons|Category:Znamenny chant}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130613084202/http://www.churchofthenativity.net/old-rite/znamenny Explanation and History of Znamenny Chant]\n*[http://www.synaxis.info/psalom/index.html Traditional Eastern Orthodox Chant Documentation Project] \u2013 a lot of information and notes. (English)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050115060306/http://www.geocities.com/pliguzov/ Observations on the Early Russian Collections of the Library of Congress] \u2013 references to Znamenny Chant\n*[http://www.acrod.org/ministries/music/plainchant/pchistorypt1 The History of Plain Chant]\n*{{ChoralWiki|Znamenny chant|prep=of}}\n\n{{Chant}}\n{{Musical notation}}\n\n[[Category:Christian chants]]\n[[Category:Russian liturgical music]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian music]]\n[[Category:Musical notation]]\n[[Category:Musicology]]\n[[Category:Old Believer movement]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Znamenny Icon of the Theotokos|Our Lady of the Sign}}\n[[Image:Example of hooks and banners notation.PNG|thumb|300px|right|An example of Znamenny notation with so-called \"red marks\", Russia, 1884. \"Thy [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Cross]] we honour, oh Lord, and Thy holy Resurrection we praise.\"]]\n\n'''Znamenny Chant''' ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435, \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0432}}) is a singing tradition used by some in the [[Russia]]n [[Orthodox Church]]. Znamenny Chant is [[unison]], [[melisma]]tic [[liturgy|liturgical]] singing that has its own specific notation, called the ''stolp'' notation.  The symbols used in the stolp notation are called ''{{transl|ru|kryuki|links=no}}'' ({{lang-ru|\u043a\u0440\u044e\u043a\u0438|links=no}}, 'hooks') or ''{{transl|ru|znamena}}'' ({{lang-ru|\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0451\u043d\u0430|links=no}}, 'signs').  Often the names of the signs are used to refer to the stolp notation.  Znamenny melodies are part of a system, consisting of Eight Tones (intonation structures; called glasy); the melodies are characterized by fluency and well-balancedness {{harv|Kholopov|2003|loc=192}}. There exist several types of Znamenny Chant: the so-called ''Stolpovoy'', ''Malyj'' (Little) and ''Bolshoy'' (Great) Znamenny Chant.  Ruthenian Chant ([[Prostopinije]]) is sometimes considered a sub-division of the Znamenny Chant tradition, with the [[Grand Duchy of Moscow|Muscovite]] Chant (Znamenny Chant proper) being the second branch of the same musical continuum.\n\n==Notation==\nZnamenny Chants are not written with notes (the so-called linear notation), but with special signs, called ''Znam\u00ebna'' (Russian for \"marks\", \"banners\") or ''Kryuki'' (\"hooks\"), as some shapes of these signs resemble hooks. Each sign may include the following components: a large black hook or a black stroke, several smaller black 'points' and 'commas' and lines near the hook or crossing the hook. Some signs may mean only one note, some 2 to 4 notes, and some a whole melody of more than 10 notes with a complicated rhythmic structure. [[Image:Kryuki.jpg|thumb|200px|A hand-drawn [[lubok]] featuring 'hook and banner notation'.]]\n\nThe stolp notation was developed in [[Kievan Rus']] as an [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] refinement of the [[Byzantine music|Byzantine]] [[neumatic]] musical notation.\n\nThe most notable feature of this notation system is that it records transitions of the melody, rather than [[Musical note|note]]s. The signs also represent a mood and a gradation of how this part of melody is to be sung (tempo, strength, devotion, meekness, etc.) Every sign has its own name and also features as a spiritual symbol. For example, there is a specific sign, called \"little dove\" (Russian: \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u0447\u0438\u043a ''(golubchik)''), which represents two rising sounds, but which is also a symbol of the [[Holy Ghost]].\n\nAfter the fall of Kievan Rus' to the [[Mongols]], the Znamenny Chant and stolp notation continued to develop to the North (particularly in [[Novgorod]]), where it flourished and was adopted throughout the [[Grand Duchy of Moscow]].\n\nGradually the system became more and more complicated. This system was also ambiguous, so that almost no one, except the most trained and educated singers, could sing an unknown melody at sight. The signs only helped to reproduce the melody, not coding it in an unambiguous way.\n\nBecause of the complexity of the system, a simplification was developed by Ivan Shaidurov around 1600,<ref>Velimirovic, Milos. \"The Present status of Research in Slavic Chant\". ''Acta Musicologica''. Vol. 44, Fasc. 2 (Jul. - Dec., 1972), pp. 251</ref> called \"red marks\" (Russian: \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u0438 (''kinovarnye znaki'')), which consisted of small letters in red and which were placed before each Znamenny sign. These indicate the highest note of the sign it stands before. This is generally regarded as the first step towards a certain simplification of the system.\n\nThe use and evolution of the system stopped in the middle of the 17th century, after the [[raskol|church reforms]] by [[Patriarch Nikon]]. From that time Western music started to penetrate into Russian culture, and the Russian-Orthodox Church introduced a \"Latin\", polyphonic way of singing, based on Polish, German and Italian harmonies. The term \"Latin\" however was considered derogatory, since it also referred to \"heretical Latin faith\".  Znamenny Chant, however, has been preserved to a certain degree in the chanting traditions that are directly descended from it.\n\n[[File:\u0424\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041a\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u0438\u043d. \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0445\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0415\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0430\u044f, \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441 1. \u0420\u0430\u0441\u0448\u0438\u0444\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u041c. \u0412..ogg|thumb|left|Fyodor Krestianin (i.e. Christian). Sticheron first of Gospel, mode 1. Transcribing of M.Brazhnikov]]\nCurrently, stolp notation (Znamenny signs) continues to be used by Russian [[Old Believers]], mostly in combination with the above-mentioned \"red marks\", as shown in the first illustration. In the 19th century [[Edinovertsy]], particularly outside Russia, have tried to move to the modern neumatic form of notation that tries to capture exact relations between [[pitch (music)|pitch]]es; and they currently use a standard [[musical notation|linear notation]].\n\nChanting traditions that preserve and/or are descended from the Znammeny chant include the following:\n\n* Chanting traditions of the Russian [[Old Believers]]\n** Znamenny chant proper (\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f, \u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0435 \u0417\u043d\u0430\u043c\u044f)\n** Stolpovoy chant\n** [[Demesvenny chant]] or ''Demestvo'' (\u0414\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e)\n** [[Pomorsky chant]]\n** [[Kievan chant]]\n* '[[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] Chants'\n** The chanting tradition of [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]] (known as [[Samoilka]] chant)\n** [[Prostopinije]] (or Plain Chant) of the [[Rusyns|Carpatho-Rusyns]]\n* [[Valaam chant]]\n*  Doukhobor Psalm chant may also be derivative or at least related\ncf. F. Mark Mealing/Our People's Way/A Study in Doukhobor Hymnody & Folklife. U. Penna, 1972.\nThe [[Strochnoy chant]] (early Russian [[polyphony]]) was also based on Znamenny chant, and although it is not widely used in the church practice now, it can be occasionally performed by some choirs. Many Russian composers ([[Sergei Rachmaninov]], [[Alexander Grechaninov]], [[Maximilian Steinberg]], and [[Vladimir Martynov]]) studied Znamenny chants and used them in their compositions. There are also many adaptations of Znamenny melodies for four-part choir, popular in both Russia and abroad.\n\n==Performing practice==\nBecause Znamenny Chant requires a specific manner of performance, the chant books contain several instructions as to dynamics and tempo. For the Old Believers church chant also has an educational function: one has to sing in such a way that the sound astonishes the ear and the truth, enclosed in the chants, penetrates the heart. Znamenny performance practice excludes classical vocal training.  Singers perform with their own, natural voices, sometimes in a style reminiscent of folk music. Znamenny Chant does not have any pauses or rests, and all chants are performed fluently. Ideally, singers will sing in such a way that their voices become united in one single voice.   \nOriginally Znamenny Chant was performed only by male voices. Today, on account of the small number of people able to sing at church services and the evolution of the tradition, it is usually performed by both male and female voices.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Kholopov|2003}}|reference=[[Yuri Kholopov|Kholopov, Yuri]] (2003). ''\u0413\u0430\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u0422\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441''. 2nd ed. Moscow; Saint Petersburg: Lan'. {{ISBN|5-8114-0516-2}} (English: Harmony. A Theoretical Course; the 1st ed. is Moscow, 1988)}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* \u0412\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0444\u0442 \u0421.\u0413., \u0423\u0448\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0418.\u0410. \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0440\u044f\u0434\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e. \u041b\u0438\u0446\u0430, \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u044f, \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043c\u0435\u0442\u044b \u0438 \u0441\u0438\u043c\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044b. \u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442 \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f, \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430 1996 / Vurgaft S.G., U\u0161akov I.A. Staroobrjad\u010destvo. Lica, sobytija, predmety i simvoly. Opyt \u0117nciklopedi\u010deskogo slovarja, Moskva 1996 \n* Reynolds, Steven.  \"Carpatho-Rusyn American\", Vol. II (1979), No. 3.  Carpatho-Rusyn Research Society.\n\n==External links ==\n{{commons|Category:Znamenny chant}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130613084202/http://www.churchofthenativity.net/old-rite/znamenny Explanation and History of Znamenny Chant]\n*[http://www.synaxis.info/psalom/index.html Traditional Eastern Orthodox Chant Documentation Project] - a lot of information and notes. (English)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050115060306/http://www.geocities.com/pliguzov/ Observations on the Early Russian Collections of the Library of Congress] - references to Znamenny Chant\n*[http://www.acrod.org/ministries/music/plainchant/pchistorypt1 The History of Plain Chant]\n*{{ChoralWiki|Znamenny chant|prep=of}}\n\n{{Chant}}\n{{Musical notation}}\n\n[[Category:Christian chants]]\n[[Category:Russian liturgical music]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian music]]\n[[Category:Musical notation]]\n[[Category:Musicology]]\n[[Category:Old Believer movement]]\n", "name_user": "Jerome Kohl", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Znamenny_chant"}
{"title_page": "Hall High School (Connecticut)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                = William H. Hall High School\n|image               =\n|imagesize           = \n|motto               = 'Live like a Warrior!'\n|streetaddress       = 975 North Main Street\n|city                = [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]]\n|state               = [[Connecticut]]\n|zipcode             = 06117\n|country             = [[United States]]\n|district            = [[West Hartford Public Schools]]\n|established         = 1924<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web |url=https://patch.com/connecticut/westhartford/what-year-was-this-team-picture-taken |title=What Year Was this Team Picture Taken? |last=Newton |first=Ronni |date=April 30, 2012 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|coordinates         = {{coord|41.7946|-72.7513|display=inline,title}}\n|type                = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[high school]]\n|principal           = Dan Zittoun\n|superintendent      = Tom Moore\n|grades              = [[Ninth grade|9]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|campus              =\n|founder             = William H. Hall\n|faculty             = 97 (2014\u201315)\n|students            = 1,447 (2016-17)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0904920&ID=090492001015|title=Hall High School|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|team_name           = Warriors\n|colors              = Blue and White {{color box|blue}}{{color box|white}}\n|newspaper           = 'Hall Highlights'\n|yearbook            = 'Hallmarks'\n|rivals              = [[Conard High School]]\n|homepage            = [http://hall.whps.org/ Official Site]\n|footnotes           = Source:<ref name=\"us news overview\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/william-h-hall-high-school-4566 |title=Hall High School in West Hartford, CT |website=US News |date=2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> except where noted\n}}\n\n'''William H. Hall High School,''' also known as '''Hall High''', is a four-year public [[high school]] located in [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Connecticut]]. Opened in 1924, it was named after William Henry Hall, who was a teacher, principal, and superintendent of schools in West Hartford.<ref name=\"history\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whps.org/uploaded/Schools/High_Schools/Hall_High_School/Students/2017-2018_William_H._Hall_High_School_Student_Handbook_-_Final.pdf?1503332266992 |title=William H. Hall High School Student Handbook 2017\u20132018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The school colors are [[blue]] and [[white (color)|white]], and the mascot is the \"Warrior\". It is one of two public high schools in the [[West Hartford Public Schools]], the other being [[Conard High School]]. Enrollment in grades 9\u201312 for the 2014\u20132015 school year was 1,437 students.<ref name=\"us news overview\"/>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe 2014\u20132015 demographic profile is as follows: White 65%, Hispanic 12%, Asian American 10%, Black 10%, two or more races 3%, American Indian/Alaskan Native 1%, and Hawaiian Native/Pacific Islander 0.1%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/connecticut/districts/west-hartford-school-district/hall-high-school-4566/student-body |title=Hall High School Student Body |website=U.S. News & World Report |date=2017 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics and clubs==\nIn soccer, Hall won the 1980 state championship 3-2 over [[E. O. Smith High School]]. The school also reached the semifinals of the state tournament four times under head coach Zeke Seguro, who won his 150th game as coach on October 10, 2008 with a 1-0 victory at South Windsor. In 2018, the Hall boys lost 1-0 to Glastonbury in the state championship. However, they won the 2019 state championship 3-1 over Greenwich. Hall's boys' cross country team has won the Central Connecticut Conference four of the last five years dating back to 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://centralconnecticutconference.org/index.php/championship-meets-crosscountry-b-2798 |title=Cross Country Archives: Championship Meets |website=Central Connecticut Conference |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHall's boys indoor track team won both Class LL Championships and the CT State Open Championships in 2019. {{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nHall has a renowned jazz program, which stage an annual production called Pops <nowiki>'n' Jazz, regularly selling over 3,000 tickets every year. They have also won the Essentially Ellington High School Jazz Band Competition and Festival twice, in 1998 and 2000. The band has performed for the president at the White House, appeared in Ken Burns's documentary film ''Jazz''</nowiki> and shared the stage with countless jazz luminaries, including Count Basie Orchestra, Wynton Marsalis,  Jimmy Heath, Ted Nash, Arturo O'Farrell, Elliot Mason, John Daversa, Phil Woods and Joe Lovano.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/13/nyregion/not-just-another-school-band-recital.html |title=Not Just Another School Band Recital |last=Staudter |first=Thomas |date=May 13, 2001 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 5, 2016 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Hall's chess team won the state championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.westhartfordnews.com/news/hall-chess-team-wins-state-championship/article_76befc93-5e53-5fe4-a8e9-862b6e9f61b9.html |title=Hall Chess Team wins State Championship |date=June 23, 2011 |access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Academic accomplishments==\n*[[Blue Ribbon Schools Program|Blue Ribbon School]] in 1984\u201385.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/programs/nclbbrs/list-1982.pdf |title=Archived Information: Blue Ribbon Schools Program: Schools Recognized 1982\u20131983 Through 1999